sec.p:
In a study by De-la-Colina et al. in 201642, it was stated that the aspect ratio of a building’s plan plays a crucial role in determining accidental eccentricity. Buildings with square plans (aspect ratio of 1) are less susceptible to accidental eccentricity than those with rectangular plans (aspect ratio higher or lower than 1). This observation is in line with other studies9,43,44. Additionally, buildings with square plans have a higher amplification factor (Ax) than those with rectangular plans, which can cause higher accidental eccentricity. However, the maximum accidental eccentricity occurs in rectangular buildings, as seen in Fig. 10a and c. In Fig. 10b, the maximum accidental eccentricity obtained by the proposed method at As = 4 is selected, with a value of 1.47 m. This value is crucial in determining the maximum frequency ratio (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
